title: For Trade:  Springfield Armory M1 Garand
postcontent:
Putting this out as a feeler... 

Up for trade only is a SA M1 Garand. It shoots great (tears up a 2 liter Coke bottle at 100 yards with Greek surplus), but I can't bring myself to do anything other than stair at it due to the historical importance. This gun, judging by serial numbers and parts, definitely saw action in World War II and Korea.  Gun is in great shape with a conservative 85% finish.

Though it's a service gun, it is ALL Springfield Armory from what I can tell. Stock was refinished or replaced at some point (no cartouches), but appears to have the original wood on top of the barrel. The lack of cartouches is common on replacement stocks sent abroad. Rifling is still good, but the barrel was counterbored at some point due to what was probably a dinged up muzzle crown (thus improving accuracy). This was commonly done to these rifles by civilians when they were as cheap and readily available as Mosin Nagants. 

Bullet still sits in the muzzle with the proper 1/16"+ gap between bullet and brass. Again, this is a tack driver for a 67 year old gun with a 59 year old barrel!

Receiver: SA (January 1944)
Bolt: SA (Revision 19 [Post November 1944])
Barrel: SA (December 1952)
Trigger Guard: SA (Type 1 [Pre 1944])
Op Rod: SA (Post WWII production [Older ones cracked after repeated use. Probably put in when rebarreled])

WHAT YOU GET: Gun will come with period correct sling, rifle case, and 192 rounds of Greek HPX on enbloc clips in bandoleers WITH THE CARDBOARD in an ammo can.

TRADE VALUE: $900
This gun is gorgeous and would be worth far more if the economy was better. They don't make these anymore folks, and finding a surplus gun in this shape with all SA parts is uncommon!

title: For Sale:  NFA Class III Gun Trusts
postcontent:
Private ownership requires friendly local chief or sheriff signature, fingerprints and photos, and when you are not present leaves your loved ones with constructive possession issues.  An LLC requires annual fees and state filings or the LLC defaults leaving both you and your loved ones in possession of a restricted item.

A trust is an BATFE approved method of Class III item ownership that protects you, protects your friends and family from constructive possession issues and give you the control over when and where your items will be transferred after your death - all without a second $200 transfer stamp!  Generic and fill-in-the-blank asset or estate trusts from the internet or quicken are not good enough.  It may be enough for the application, but it might not be good enough should BATFE ever have a reason to look closer.  Do it right the first time with a trust that is NFA specific and OVER-complaint.  There are five provision that every NFA trust should have that are not present in a general asset trust!

I am the only attorney in Kansas that I know of that has experience with NFA gun trusts and is providing this service.  

R. Todd King
King, Brennan & Albin LLC
221 S. Topeka
Wichita KS 67202

title: For Sale:  Bulgarian Makarov
postcontent:
This Makarov pistol was made in Bulgaria in 1978 (the 4th year of production; Bulgarian arsenal year code 18) and bears the "Circle 10" arsenal mark of the Bulgarian military.  It was imported to the US by PW Arms.  I purchased it on January 27, 2004, and have cared for it meticulously since then, cleaning it thoroughly and lubricating it lightly after every shooting session.  I estimate I have put 450 rounds through it.  The pictures tell the story of the condition.  Note the discreet importer's mark above the grip on the right side, instead of the billboard placard on the slide so common with most Bulgarian Makarovs.  The bore is mirror bright and rifling is sharp.  Slide and frame serial numbers match.  High resolution pictures are available on request.

This pistol comes with everything with which it was imported -- the original cardboard box and wrapping paper (serial number on box matches pistol), standard issue red military grips, black thumbrest grips, and two Bulgarian 8 round magazines.

These military pistols did not come with an owners manual, but Century Arms created and published a simple one.  To see an electronic copy of the CAI manual, go here:  http://stevespages.com/pdf/makarov.pdf.

FTF transaction only.  Must present government picture ID showing you are a resident of Ohio of legal age to purchase this firearm.

Why some scopes lose their zeros and some don't?
 Rule #1 is: In order for a scope to lose its zero, something between the reticle and the target must move.
 Rule #2 is: In order to see what moved you need two reticles, each one to track the other.


The old type German scopes put the cross hair in the front focal plane. They hardly ever lost their zeros because the only thing between the reticle and the cross hair was the objective lens. The drawback was that the reticle magnified when zoomed and blocked out long-range targets. Americans put the reticle in the rear focal plane where it would not magnify. The main drawback with this was that it put about three more lenses between the reticle and the target. The American system was then three times more likely to lose its zero. The American was more convenient but the German system was more reliable.

Shepherd Rifle Scope gives you the best of both worlds with the drawbacks of neither. Sheperd uses the front focal plane location for rangefinding and bullet drop compensating circles. This gives Shepperd Scope the German dependability and, when zoomed, the circles do not block the targets but instead frame them and give you instant target engagement on any power. Then put the cross hair in the rearfocal plane (where the Americans do) in order to get the benefits of a nonmagnifying reticle. This patented Dual Reticle System lets each reticle monitor the other and thus allows for: one shot zeroing in, "at a glance" verification of the original zero, and visual confirmation of windage and elevation adjustments before you shoot. The Shepherd is truly the most reliable of all and the only one to tell you if something is out of zero before you shoot.

title: For Sale:  Vintage WWII Webley & Scott Mark IV Flare Gun Pistol WWII
location: Lake Mead & Jones, Nevada, United States
postcontent: Vintage WWII British / Canadian forces used these Webley & Scott Mark IV Flare Gun / Pistols. $250 o.b.o Zinc coated, 37mm, 5 1/2" barrel, trigger action works, beautiful patina, very rare and hard to find. These guns were made about 1939 in Australia for British forces during WWII. This one comes with a Vintage carved Pine or Cedar wood box that it was found in. The handle is cracked and chipped, but otherwise it is in firing condition. I was only able to find one other of these for sale online and it was in similar condition. This is a great item for the Vintage / Antique gun collector or WWII / Military collector. Here is some more info: Webley & Scott produced a number of single-shot, break open signal flare gun devices used by Commonwealth Military Forces during the First and Second World Wars. Perhaps the most prolific of these was the No.1 MkIII, produced in 1918 at the company's Birmingham facility. A variant, differing only in its use of black plastic grip panels instead of the earlier wood, was produced by Colonial Sugar Refinery in Sydney, Australia in 1942. The pistols can often be seen in films, notably Lawrence of Arabia, where the title character discharges one to signal the beginning of an attack on a disabled enemy train, and The Empire Strikes Back where bounty hunter Boba Fett is seen carrying one as a rifle. Call / Text Landon - REDACTED Las Vegas / Lake Mead & Jones
